Quick Paths
arXiv 2509.04259 • September 2025

RL's Razor: Why Online Reinforcement Learning Forgets Less

On-policy RL is implicitly biased toward KL-minimal solutions, and KL divergence on the new task reliably predicts catastrophic forgetting.

Authors: Idan Shenfeld, Jyothish Pari, Pulkit Agrawal
Institution: Improbable AI Lab, MIT CSAIL
§ 1

TL;DR / Executive Summary

One-Sentence Summary
When fine-tuning foundation models, RL forgets less than SFT because on-policy RL is implicitly biased toward KL-minimal solutions, and KL divergence on the new task reliably predicts the degree of catastrophic forgetting.
4/4
Tasks where RL dominates SFT
0.96
R² KL predicts forgetting (MNIST)
0.71
R² KL predicts forgetting (LLMs)
0
KL regularization needed

This paper establishes that reinforcement learning fine-tuning forgets significantly less than supervised fine-tuning at matched new-task performance, and identifies the mechanism: forward KL divergence from the base model, measured only on the new task, is a near-perfect predictor of catastrophic forgetting (R²=0.96 on MNIST, 0.71 on LLMs).

The key theoretical contribution is showing that on-policy RL is implicitly biased toward KL-minimal solutions via an EM-like alternating projection in distribution space -- not because of negative examples, explicit regularization, or sparse updates, but because sampling from the model's own distribution constrains the optimization to nearby solutions.

The authors validate this by constructing an oracle SFT distribution that provably minimizes KL divergence and achieves even less forgetting than RL, demonstrating that forgetting is a distributional phenomenon governed by how far the fine-tuned model's output distribution drifts from the base, not by the training algorithm itself.

Bottom Line

If you are fine-tuning a foundation model on a new task and care about preserving prior capabilities, measure forward KL divergence on the new task during training -- it will tell you how much you are forgetting without ever needing access to old-task data. Better yet, use on-policy RL or engineer KL-minimal training distributions to get the same new-task performance with dramatically less forgetting.

Figure 1: Bias toward KL-minimal solutions reduces forgetting. Left: Among policies solving the new task, RL converges to those closest in KL to the base model. Right: This yields higher prior-task retention at matched new-task performance.

The left panel shows that among the many policies that solve a new task equally well (gray oval), RL (red dot) converges to those closest in KL divergence to the base model, while SFT (blue dot) converges to distant policies. § 2

RL Forgets Less Than SFT

Key Finding (Section 3)
Across four tasks (LLM math, science Q&A, tool use, and robotic pick-and-place), RL's Pareto frontier for new-task performance versus prior-task retention consistently dominates SFT's. At matched new-task accuracy, RL-tuned models retain substantially higher scores on unrelated benchmarks.

The authors fine-tuned the same base models using two post-training strategies -- supervised fine-tuning (SFT) and reinforcement learning with GRPO -- on identical sets of prompts. For each method, they trained dozens of models across a broad sweep of hyperparameters. They then evaluated every checkpoint on two axes: performance on the new task's held-out test set, and average performance on a battery of unrelated benchmarks that proxy for "prior knowledge."

By plotting every trained model as a point in this two-dimensional space and tracing the Pareto frontier -- the curve of models where you cannot improve on the new task without sacrificing more prior knowledge -- they obtained a fair, hyperparameter-agnostic comparison.

The results are striking across all four experimental settings. For LLM tasks (Qwen 2.5 3B-Instruct on math reasoning, science Q&A, and tool use), RL's frontier sits above and to the right of SFT's. The gap is most dramatic in math, where even small SFT gains trigger steep forgetting. The same pattern holds for robotics, where OpenVLA 7B was fine-tuned on a pick-and-place can task and evaluated on drawer opening/closing tasks.

Analogy

Think of it like learning a new language. RL is like learning by practicing with a native speaker -- you adapt your existing speech patterns gradually, preserving your accent and grammar from your first language. SFT is like memorizing a phrasebook word-for-word -- you overwrite your existing patterns with fixed templates, and your fluency in your first language degrades.

Importantly, the RL experiments used only a binary success reward with no explicit KL regularization, meaning the reduced forgetting is not because RL was explicitly told to stay close to the base model. It emerges naturally from how RL trains.

Figure 2: Pareto frontiers of RL and SFT. Each point is a model trained with different hyperparameters. Curves trace the Pareto frontiers. RL (red) consistently dominates SFT (blue).
What This Shows

This is the primary empirical evidence. Across four diverse domains, RL consistently achieves a better forgetting-performance trade-off than SFT. Each dot represents a model trained with different hyperparameters, so the comparison controls for hyperparameter tuning.

Experimental Details

The four experimental tasks span two modalities and three LLM domains:

  • LLM Math Reasoning: Qwen 2.5 3B-Instruct fine-tuned on Open-Reasoner-Zero. SFT annotations generated by DeepSeek R1. RL used GRPO with binary correctness reward.
  • LLM Science Q&A: Qwen 2.5 3B-Instruct on SciKnowEval Chemistry L-3. SFT annotations via GPT-4o.
  • LLM Tool Use: Qwen 2.5 3B-Instruct on ToolAlpaca. Evaluation extracted API calls via regex matching.
  • Robotics Pick and Place: OpenVLA 7B in SimplerEnv. Training data collected over 10x10 grid. Forgetting measured on drawer open/close tasks.

For LLMs, forgetting was measured using the Language Model Evaluation Harness across six benchmarks: HellaSwag, TruthfulQA, MMLU, IFEval, Winogrande, and HumanEval.

Pareto frontier construction followed a five-step protocol: (1) hyperparameter sweep producing dozens of trained models per method; (2) new-task evaluation; (3) previous-task evaluation on full benchmark suite; (4) Pareto filtering (within 2 accuracy points of frontier); (5) exponential curve fitting.

§ 3

KL Divergence Predicts Forgetting

Key Finding (Section 4)
The degree of catastrophic forgetting is predicted by a single number: the forward KL divergence between the base and fine-tuned model on the new task. A quadratic fit achieves R² = 0.96 on ParityMNIST and R² = 0.71 on LLM experiments. The training algorithm does not matter -- only how far the distribution drifts.

KL divergence measures how different two probability distributions are. In this context, it quantifies how much the fine-tuned model's output distribution has shifted away from the base model's, but crucially, measured only on inputs from the new task -- not the old tasks. This is what makes the finding practically useful: you do not need access to previous task data to estimate how much the model has forgotten.

When the authors plotted forgetting against KL divergence on the ParityMNIST testbed, all five fine-tuning strategies -- RL, RL with KL regularization, and three different SFT variants -- collapsed onto a single smooth curve. The method of training did not matter; what mattered was how far the model's outputs drifted from the base model on the new task.

Analogy

Think of KL divergence as measuring how much the model's "accent" has changed when speaking the new language. A bigger accent change -- even if it helps with the new language -- means more forgetting of the old one. What is surprising is that you only need to listen to the model speak the new language to predict how much of the old language it has lost.

To validate that KL is genuinely the causal variable and not just a correlate, the authors constructed an oracle SFT distribution: the labeling that provably minimizes KL while achieving perfect accuracy. Training SFT on this oracle distribution produced even less forgetting than RL, confirming the causal chain: lower KL leads to less forgetting, regardless of algorithm.

Figure 3: KL divergence predicts catastrophic forgetting. Middle: All methods collapse to a single curve when plotted against KL (R² = 0.961). Right: RL achieves high accuracy with smaller KL shifts.
What This Shows

The Empirical Forgetting Law

The empirical forgetting law states that for a model \(\pi\) fine-tuned from base model \(\pi_0\) on a new task with input distribution \(\tau\), the degree of catastrophic forgetting is a function of:

\[ \mathbb{E}_{x \sim \tau}\left[D_{KL}(\pi_0(\cdot|x) \| \pi(\cdot|x))\right] \]
Forward KL divergence from base to fine-tuned model on new-task inputs

Where \(D_{KL}(\pi_0 \| \pi) = \sum_y \pi_0(y|x) \log \frac{\pi_0(y|x)}{\pi(y|x)}\) is the forward KL divergence, and the expectation is over inputs from the new task distribution. Note: this is the forward KL (base model in the first argument), not the reverse KL.

The relationship is quadratic, not linear: small KL shifts cause minimal forgetting, but forgetting accelerates nonlinearly as KL grows. This was validated with five fine-tuning strategies on ParityMNIST producing ~500 runs each:

  • GRPO: On-policy RL with normalized reward advantages
  • GRPO + KL regularization: Coefficient 0.1
  • SFT 1: All even digits mapped to label 0, all odd to label 1
  • SFT 2: Even digits mapped to {0, 4}, odd to {1, 5}
  • Oracle SFT: Labels drawn from the KL-minimal distribution

LLM Validation

Figure 11: KL divergence vs. average prior-task score for LLM experiments. RL (red) clusters at low KL, SFT (blue) at high KL. R² = 0.71.
What This Shows

The KL-forgetting relationship discovered in ParityMNIST also holds in full-scale LLM experiments (R² = 0.71). RL models consistently cluster at lower KL divergence. The weaker R² is attributed to noise from approximate KL estimation at LLM scale.

Computing Forward KL

For discrete outputs (MNIST): compute full softmax distributions \(\pi_0(\cdot|x)\) and \(\pi(\cdot|x)\) for each test input x. Compute KL analytically. Average over x.

For LLMs: sample outputs, use log-probability estimates. Approximation necessary since exact KL computation is intractable for autoregressive LLMs with large output spaces.

Practical Tip

The forward KL (base model first) is the correct direction; reverse KL (R² = 0.93) and TV (R² = 0.80) are weaker predictors. For LLMs, approximate KL can still be a useful monitoring signal during training even though exact computation is infeasible.

§ 4

On-Policy Methods Lead to Smaller KL

Key Finding (Section 5)
The critical factor for RL's reduced forgetting is on-policy training (sampling from the model's own distribution), not the use of negative examples. 1-0 Reinforce (on-policy, no negatives) behaves like GRPO, while SimPO (offline, with negatives) behaves like SFT. This directly contradicts concurrent work attributing RL's advantage to negative examples.

SFT and RL differ in two ways: where the training data comes from (on-policy vs. external annotations), and whether negative examples (wrong answers that get pushed away) are used. The authors designed a four-way experiment to test which factor actually matters.

The four methods form a 2x2 grid:

  • GRPO: On-policy, with negative examples
  • 1-0 Reinforce: On-policy, without negative examples (keeps correct responses with advantage 1, discards incorrect with advantage 0)
  • SFT: Offline, without negative examples
  • SimPO: Offline, with negative examples

The results were unambiguous: GRPO and 1-0 Reinforce behaved nearly identically, both achieving strong new-task accuracy with minimal KL shift. SFT and SimPO also behaved nearly identically, both incurring large KL shifts. The presence or absence of negative examples made no difference; what mattered was whether the training sampled from the model itself.

Analogy

Think of it like a chef improving a recipe. On-policy training is like tasting variations of your own cooking and keeping what works -- you stay close to your existing style. Off-policy training is like trying to replicate someone else's recipe from a cookbook -- you might end up with a completely different cooking style, losing your original techniques.

Figure 4: Comparison of algorithm classes. On-policy methods (GRPO, 1-0 Reinforce) achieve higher accuracy with smaller KL shifts and less forgetting than offline methods (SFT, SimPO).
What This Shows

This ablation disentangles the two features distinguishing RL from SFT. The result is decisive: the on-policy vs. offline axis is the determining factor. Negative examples do not contribute to reduced forgetting.

How to Read This
Start here: Begin with the left quadrant diagram to understand the 2x2 design. Then look at the middle panel: on-policy methods (regardless of negative examples) cluster at low KL. The right panel confirms on-policy methods have better Pareto frontiers.
Key Takeaway

The critical factor is whether the method is on-policy (sampling from the current model) or offline (training on fixed external data). Negative examples do not explain RL's forgetting advantage.

Subfigure Breakdown

The Two Objectives

\[ L_{\text{SFT}}(\pi) = -\mathbb{E}_{x \sim D, y \sim \pi_\beta}[\log \pi(y|x)] \]
SFT Loss: \(y\) sampled from fixed external distribution \(\pi_\beta\)

SFT maximizes the probability of externally provided "correct" answers. Because the target distribution \(\pi_\beta\) is fixed and potentially far from the base model, SFT can pull the policy toward an arbitrary distribution.

\[ L_{\text{RL}}(\pi) = -\mathbb{E}_{x \sim D, y \sim \pi}[A(x,y) \log \pi(y|x)] \]
RL Loss: \(y\) sampled from the model's OWN distribution \(\pi\)

RL samples from the model itself, then reweights based on reward (advantage). Two key differences from SFT: (1) samples come from the model's own distribution (on-policy), (2) incorrect responses get negative advantage. The on-policy nature keeps updates close to the current distribution.

Implementation: The Four Methods

MethodSamplingNegative Examples?KL at Matched Accuracy

1-0 ReinforceOn-policyNo (A=1 correct, A=0 incorrect)< 2
SFTOfflineNo3-6
SimPOOfflineYes (logistic preference)3-6
Practical Tip

1-0 Reinforce is simpler to implement than GRPO (no group normalization, no negative gradient computation) and achieves equivalent forgetting behavior. It can serve as a minimal-complexity on-policy baseline for any setting where reduced forgetting is desired.

§ 5

Alternative Hypotheses Eliminated

Key Finding (Section 6)
Forward KL divergence outperforms all 10 tested alternative predictors of forgetting. Weight changes, representation shifts, sparsity of updates, and other distributional measures all fail to match forward KL's R² = 0.96. The "sparse RL updates" hypothesis was debunked as a bfloat16 precision artifact.

The authors systematically tested every plausible alternative explanation for catastrophic forgetting, grouped into four categories:

  • Weight-level changes (L1, Fisher-weighted L2, spectral norm): Correlated only weakly (R² 0.34-0.58). Large parameter shifts sometimes occurred without forgetting.
  • Representation-level changes (activation L1 and L2): Showed some correlation but differed between objectives (R² 0.52-0.55).
  • Sparsity/rank of updates: An artifact of bfloat16 precision. float32 training eliminated sparsity differences with no change in performance. All methods produce full-rank updates.
  • Other distributional distances (reverse KL, TV, L2): Forward KL was the clear winner.
Table 1: Predictive power of alternative variables compared to forward KL divergence. None approaches the explanatory strength of forward KL.
What This Shows

This table systematically compares candidate predictors. Forward KL divergence at R² = 0.96 far exceeds all alternatives: reverse KL (0.93), TV (0.80), weight metrics (0.34-0.58), and activation metrics (0.52-0.55). Sparsity and rank show no predictive signal.

Key Takeaway

Decades of weight-space interventions for forgetting (EWC, synaptic intelligence, sparse updates) were treating symptoms. The disease is distributional -- forward KL divergence is the only reliable predictor.

The forward direction matters because it penalizes cases where the base model assigns probability to outputs the fine-tuned model ignores -- precisely the scenario of lost capabilities.

The bfloat16 Sparsity Artifact

bfloat16 has a 7-bit mantissa (vs. float32's 23-bit). When parameter updates are small (as in RL's conservative steps), the update may round to zero. This creates artificial sparsity. Running the same experiments in float32 eliminated all sparsity differences with no change in model performance.

§ 6

Theoretical Foundation: Policy Gradient as EM

Key Result (Section 5.2)
Policy gradient with binary reward provably converges to the KL-minimal optimal policy -- the closest feasible solution to the starting model that perfectly solves the new task. This is formalized as an EM algorithm with information projections (Theorem 5.2), requiring no explicit KL regularization.

The key insight is that policy gradient can be decomposed into two alternating steps, much like the classical Expectation-Maximization (EM) algorithm:

  • E-step (I-projection): The current policy samples responses and keeps only the correct ones. This is equivalent to rejection sampling, which produces the distribution closest in KL divergence to the current policy among all distributions achieving perfect reward.
  • M-step (M-projection): The model parameters are updated to best approximate this filtered distribution within the set of policies the neural network can represent.

By alternating these two steps, the algorithm traces a path through policy space that always stays near the current model while moving toward optimal policies. The formal result (Theorem 5.2) states that this process converges to the optimal policy that is closest in KL divergence to the initial model.

Intuition

It is like water finding the lowest-energy path downhill: the policy naturally flows to the nearest feasible solution rather than jumping to a distant one. On-policy sampling acts as a free KL regularizer -- no penalty coefficient required.

Figure 5: KL-minimal path to optimality. Alternating I-projection (into optimal policies) and M-projection (into feasible policies) converges to \(\pi^\dagger\), the KL-minimal optimal policy.
What This Shows

This diagram visualizes Theorem 5.2. The I-projection (rejection sampling) projects onto the optimal set \(P^*\); the M-projection (policy gradient step) projects back onto the representable policy family \(\Pi\). The alternation converges to \(\pi^\dagger\), the policy at the intersection that is closest in KL to the initialization \(\pi_0\).

How to Read This
Start here: Find \(\pi_0\) (the base policy) in the feasible region \(\Pi\). Follow the alternating arrows: first toward the optimal set (R=1), then back into \(\Pi\), spiraling toward \(\pi^\dagger\). The KL contour lines show that \(\pi^\dagger\) sits at the intersection closest to \(\pi_0\).

Formal Results

\[ q_{RS} = \arg\min_q D_{KL}(q \| p) \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \mathbb{E}_{y \sim q}[R(y)] = 1 \]
Lemma 5.1: Rejection sampling from \(p\) with acceptance \(R(y)=1\) yields the I-projection

When RL samples from the current policy and keeps only correct responses, the resulting distribution is exactly the one closest in KL to the current policy among all perfect-reward distributions. This is the I-projection step.

\[ \pi^\dagger = \arg\min_{\pi \in P^* \cap \Pi} D_{KL}(\pi \| \pi_0) \]
Theorem 5.2: Policy gradient converges to the KL-minimal optimal policy

Among all policies that are both optimal (\(P^*\): perfect reward) and representable (\(\Pi\): model family), policy gradient finds the one closest to where you started (\(\pi_0\)). This is the formal statement of RL's Razor: no explicit KL regularization is needed.

Practical Caveats

AlgorithmI-stepM-stepTheory Applies?
REINFORCE (binary R)Exact rejection samplingSGD on M-projectionYes (Thm A.3)
GRPORejection + advantage normalizationSGD on M-projectionYes (advantage = control variate)
PPORejection + clipped advantageClipped SGDApproximately
SFTN/A (no I-step)Direct projection to \(\pi_\beta\)No (not alternating)
Important Caveats

Neural networks are not e-flat: The theory is proven for exponential families. Neural network policy classes do not necessarily form exponential families, which may prevent exact convergence to the KL-minimum. However, the theory explains the observed empirical bias.

Binary rewards only: The formal theorem requires R: Y → {0,1}. Continuous rewards require additional treatment.

§ 7

The ParityMNIST Testbed

Supporting Evidence
ParityMNIST is a controlled MNIST variant where the task has multiple equally valid output distributions. It reproduces the RL-vs-SFT forgetting gap in a simple 3-layer MLP, confirming this is a general phenomenon not specific to large transformers, and enables ~500 runs per method for statistical power.

The core design insight is that the RL-vs-SFT gap requires a task with multiple valid solutions. In standard MNIST classification, there is only one correct label per image. In ParityMNIST, the task is parity classification: an image of the digit "3" is correct if the model predicts any odd digit label (1, 3, 5, 7, or 9). This means many different output distributions achieve 100% accuracy, and the question becomes which distribution the algorithm finds.

A 3-layer MLP (785-512-256-10) was pretrained jointly on ParityMNIST and FashionMNIST (500 images each). Fine-tuning was performed only on ParityMNIST, and forgetting was measured as accuracy degradation on FashionMNIST.

Why This Matters

Think of it like a math test where both "4" and "2+2" are accepted as correct answers. RL naturally picks whichever answer is closest to what the model already knows, while SFT forces one specific answer format regardless of the model's prior tendencies.

Oracle Distribution

\[ q^*(\cdot|x) = \frac{\pi_0(\cdot|x) \cdot R}{\sum_{y': R(y')=1} \pi_0(y'|x)} \]
Oracle SFT distribution: base model conditioned on correct parity

The oracle is simply the base model's distribution restricted to correct-parity labels and renormalized. For input x with base model distribution \(\pi_0(\cdot|x)\) and correct-parity indicator \(R\), this minimizes \(D_{KL}(\pi_0 \| q)\) subject to \(q^T R = 1\).

Training SFT on this oracle distribution achieves the best accuracy-forgetting trade-off observed -- better than RL -- because it targets the provably KL-minimal distribution.

Architecture and Setup

ComponentDetails
Architecture3-layer MLP: 785 → 512 (ReLU) → 256 (ReLU) → 10 (Softmax)
InputFlattened 28x28 image + binary dataset indicator (+1/-1)
Pretraining500 ParityMNIST + 500 FashionMNIST images, joint training
Learning rates15 values, log-spaced from 3e-6 to 1e-3
Schedulersconstant w/ warmup, cosine w/ warmup

Replicability

The ParityMNIST testbed can be replicated on a single GPU in minutes. It is useful for prototyping new continual-learning algorithms or testing alternative forgetting predictors before scaling to LLM experiments.

§ 8

Insights & Takeaways

Core Message
Catastrophic forgetting is governed by KL divergence from the base policy on the new task, not by the choice of training algorithm. On-policy RL implicitly minimizes this quantity, but any method that achieves low KL will forget less.
"RL's Razor: among all ways to solve a new task, on-policy RL prefers those closest in KL to the original model."
Named after Occam's Razor -- RL finds the most conservative solution.
"You can measure how much a model is forgetting without ever looking at what it is forgetting."
Forward KL on the new task predicts forgetting on old tasks, eliminating the need for old-task evaluation.
"It is the distribution, not the algorithm. Oracle SFT with the right labels beats RL -- the optimization path does not matter, only where you end up."
The most paradigm-shifting finding: forgetting is determined by the final output distribution.
"On-policy sampling is a free KL regularizer -- no penalty coefficient required."
Policy gradient implicitly performs EM with information projections.
"Decades of weight-space interventions for forgetting were treating symptoms. The disease is distributional."
EWC, synaptic intelligence, and sparse-update methods work only insofar as they constrain KL divergence.

Practical Recommendations

Priority 1: Monitor Forward KL (Low Effort, High Impact)

Periodically compute KL(base_model || fine_tuned_model) on a sample of new-task inputs. This provides the single best predictor of forgetting. Set a KL budget based on your forgetting tolerance.

Priority 2: Use On-Policy RL (Medium Effort, High Impact)

Default to on-policy methods (GRPO or REINFORCE) over SFT when forgetting matters. Even without explicit KL regularization, on-policy methods achieve lower KL and less forgetting at matched performance. Binary reward signals suffice.

Priority 3: RL-then-Distill Pipeline (Medium Effort, Medium Impact)

If RL is too expensive at scale, train a smaller RL model first, generate data from it, then train via SFT on that data. The distilled SFT will match RL's forgetting profile at SFT's computational cost.

Priority 4: Oracle Labels When Feasible (High Effort, High Impact)

For simple classification tasks, compute the KL-minimal labeling analytically (the distribution closest to the base model among all correct labelings). This can outperform even RL.

Priority 5: KL as Selection Criterion (Low Effort, Medium Impact)

During hyperparameter sweeps, add KL divergence as a second axis alongside new-task accuracy. Select configurations on the Pareto frontier of accuracy vs. KL rather than maximizing accuracy alone.

Five Core Insights

1. Predict forgetting without old task data ▼

Forward KL divergence on the new task is a reliable proxy for how much old-task performance degrades. This is deeply non-obvious -- the new-task distribution contains enough information to predict damage to unrelated capabilities. The mechanism is likely that large KL shifts reshape the model's output probability mass in ways that disrupt internal representations supporting unrelated skills.

Evidence: R²=0.96 on ParityMNIST, R²=0.71 on LLMs (Figures 3, 11). All alternatives fail to match (Table 1).

2. Distribution, not algorithm, governs forgetting ▼

Oracle SFT with KL-minimal labels achieves better trade-off than RL. SFT distilled from RL teacher matches RL's profile. RL has no magic -- its advantage comes entirely from steering toward low-KL solutions. Any method arriving at the same output distribution has the same forgetting profile.

Implication: The continual learning problem is reframed from "which algorithm to use" to "which target distribution to aim for."

3. On-policy training is an implicit KL regularizer ▼

GRPO with zero KL regularization coefficient still achieves low KL divergence. Policy gradient decomposes into alternating I-projections and M-projections (an EM algorithm) that converge to the minimum-KL solution. This is structural, not designed. Explicit KL penalties in RLHF may provide less value than assumed.

Prediction: Off-policy RL methods would forget more like SFT since they lack this implicit KL minimization.

4. Forgetting is distributional, not weight-space ▼

Weight-space metrics (L1, Fisher L2, spectral norm) are poor forgetting predictors (R² ≤ 0.58). The sparsity narrative is debunked as a bfloat16 artifact. Future continual learning methods should target distributional constraints rather than weight-space constraints.

5. Forward KL directionality matters ▼

Forward KL (base || fine-tuned) outperforms reverse KL: R² = 0.96 vs. 0.93. Forward KL penalizes the fine-tuned model for assigning low probability to tokens the base model considered likely -- measuring how much the model has "forgotten" base-model-preferred outputs. This connects to the I-projection criterion that policy gradient optimizes.

§ 9

Limitations & Open Questions

Honest Assessment
The paper establishes a strong empirical law but leaves open the mechanistic "why" of how KL shifts disrupt prior knowledge, and has not been validated at frontier scales (70B+).

Acknowledged Limitations

  • No mechanistic account: The paper establishes that KL predicts forgetting but does not explain why larger KL shifts disrupt prior knowledge -- whether through representational interference, capacity limits, or other dynamics.
  • Moderate-scale experiments only: LLM experiments use Qwen 2.5 3B-Instruct primarily, with scaling only up to 14B. Frontier-scale models (70B+) are untested.
  • Off-policy RL not studied: The paper focuses on on-policy methods (GRPO, REINFORCE). Popular off-policy RL algorithms are not examined.
  • Limited generative domains: Tasks are math, science Q&A, tool use, and robotic manipulation. More diverse domains (creative writing, code generation) are not tested.

Open Questions

  • What is the mechanistic explanation for why distributional shift on the new task causes forgetting on unrelated old tasks?
  • Does the KL-forgetting law hold for off-policy RL methods?
  • Can oracle SFT construction be scaled to complex generative tasks?
  • Is there a critical KL threshold below which forgetting is negligible, or is the relationship continuous?
  • How does the law interact with LoRA/QLoRA parameter-efficient fine-tuning?
  • How does multi-step sequential forgetting (fine-tuning on a sequence of tasks) affect cumulative KL drift?

When This Does Not Apply

  • When the new task requires fundamentally new capabilities not in the base model (KL minimization would resist the necessary shift)
  • When using off-policy RL or DPO-family methods (the implicit KL property is specific to on-policy methods)
  • At frontier scale (70B+) where behavior has not been validated
  • When forgetting is actually desirable (e.g., unlearning harmful capabilities)
  • With parameter-efficient fine-tuning (LoRA/QLoRA) where the interaction with KL is unstudied

Supplementary Evidence

Figure 7: CKA similarity to base model during training. RL preserves 94% representational similarity; SFT drops to 56%.
What This Shows

RL preserves the internal representations of the base model (CKNNA = 0.94) while SFT substantially disrupts them (CKNNA = 0.56). Measured on Wikipedia data unrelated to fine-tuning tasks, confirming the effect is about general representational change.

Figure 8: Pareto frontiers for SFT at 3B, 7B, 14B. Scaling does not reduce the forgetting rate -- larger models start higher but drop at the same rate.
What This Shows

Scaling model size from 3B to 14B does not reduce the rate of catastrophic forgetting under SFT. Larger models start with better capabilities but lose them at the same rate during fine-tuning.

Figure 9: SFT distillation from an RL teacher. SFT student matches the RL teacher's accuracy-forgetting trade-off, confirming the distribution (not algorithm) determines forgetting.
What This Shows

SFT trained on data generated by an RL teacher matches the RL teacher's forgetting profile. This proves that the distribution learned, not the optimization path, governs forgetting.

Figure 10: Gradient similarity vs. KL change. Larger per-step KL changes align more with the forgetting direction.
What This Shows

At the per-step level, larger KL divergence changes align more strongly with the forgetting direction (increasing prior-task loss). Large KL steps are doubly bad: they overshoot on the new task and cause more forgetting on prior tasks.

Figure 6: Process of creating Pareto frontier plots: all models, Pareto filtering, and exponential curve fitting.
What This Shows

The three panels show the pipeline from raw experiment data to the polished Pareto frontier curves seen in Figure 2. Step 1: Train many models with varied hyperparameters. Step 2: Select Pareto-optimal models. Step 3: Fit exponential curve to produce smooth frontiers.
